	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Long-term supply agreements emerging in Dominican Republic cocoa sector </h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 November 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A 5-year USAID-financed initiative to provide support to increase the yield and quality of cocoa production in the Dominican Republic has been announced. This forms part of a much wider global Cocoa Partnership Initiative (initially launched by Cadbury in 2008 in Ghana, where 60,000 families are being assisted through an initiative involving Kuapa Kokoo – a fair-trade cooperative – and the Cocoa Board of Ghana, as well as other programmes in India and south-east Asia, as well as the Caribbean).</p><p>The programme in the Dominican Republic aims to nurture the next generation of cocoa farmers by providing training to some 10,000 small-scale cocoa farmers on improved farming techniques and post-harvest practices. A key element of the programme is to ‘increase the supply of organic Fairtrade cocoa and provide an additional social premium for community investment and productivity improvements’. According to press reports, ‘Kraft Foods is already the world’s largest buyer of Fairtrade cocoa and organic Fairtrade cocoa.’ By the end of 2011, the aim is to convert the entire Green &amp; Black’s chocolate range to the use of organic Fairtrade-certified cocoa.</p><p>Meanwhile, after reaching a 2-year low, global cocoa prices are showing a slight recovery on the back of a year-on-year rise of 8.5% in cocoa grindings in western Europe. This however is in part linked to restocking, following the running down of inventories in the face of the earlier crisis in Côte d’Ivoire and in part linked to surging demand in ‘emerging market countries where consumption is growing strongly in part on the bean’s alleged health benefits’. The European industry is a principal supplier of these markets. However, with firm output growth in second-ranked producers such as Cameroon and Nigeria it is expected that the price resurgence will soon fall away.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Dominican Today</i>, ‘Kraft Foods and organic cacao growers strike 5-year deal’, 17 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.dominicantoday.com/dr/economy/2011/10/17/41314/Kraft-Foods-and-organic-cacao-growers-strike-5-year-deal" target="_self">http://www.dominicantoday.com/dr/economy/2011/10/17/41314/Kraft-Foods-an...</a></p><p><i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘Germany leads jump in European cocoa grindings’, 13 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/germany-leads-jump-in-european-cocoa-grind--3715.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/germany-leads-jump-in-european-cocoa-grind...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The initiative in the Dominican Republic needs to be seen against the background of efforts to develop a Caribbean cocoa collective focusing on promoting greater local value addition of fine-flavoured cocoa as the way forward for the Caribbean cocoa industry. The Caribbean is already renowned for its fine-flavoured cocoa germplasm, and seven Caribbean countries are working closely in this respect: Belize, Dominica, the Dominican Republic, Grenada, Jamaica, Haiti, and Trinidad &amp; Tobago.</p><p>Current efforts to develop the sector are focused at two levels:</p>
<ul>

<li>Improving field level productivity. This includes a joint initiative by the Cocoa Research Unit (CRU) of the University of the West Indies and the Centre for Development of Enterprise (CDE), a regional ACP-EU institution, to substantially increase farm productivity and cocoa production via support to the provision of improved planting material, the promotion of best field and bean fermentation practices, solar drying techniques and a ‘training of trainers’ programme to widely disseminate innovations in cocoa production.</li>

<li>CRU-led research on product development along cocoa value chains, including research on liqueurs, dark chocolates, pectin, syrups etc., on which a Caribbean cocoa value-added industry can be built. </li>

</ul>
<p>The support offered under the USAID-financed Cocoa Partnership Initiative with Kraft, if effectively implemented, should allow the Dominican Republic to significantly expand its farm productivity and cocoa output, and indeed foster a next generation of cocoa farmers. However it is unclear how such initiatives relate to regional efforts to promote greater local value-added processing of fine-flavoured cocoa. Potentially such agreements, even when based on ‘fair’ and organic production, still lock Caribbean producers into the export of relatively unprocessed raw materials. This can be seen as perpetuating the traditional agriculture model of producer of a raw material for export to European and North American processors.</p><p>Undoubtedly the promotion of fair-trade and organic cocoa production can offer scope for growth of the small farm sector and the wider rural economy. Of the current quality-based product differentiation schemes around, it is only fair-trade labelling schemes which guarantee additional payments to producers above and beyond the market price for cocoa (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/Product-differentiation/Trade-in-sustainable-and-organic-products-grows" target="_blank">Trade in sustainable and organic products grows</a>, May 2011). However, from the perspective of growing a world-class, value-added industry that delivers high-end products based on a premium raw material, i.e. fine-flavoured cocoa, this new arrangement may not be the best vehicle by which such goals can be achieved or sustained.</p><p>A critical challenge would appear to be ensuring that investments in improving the quality of production take place within a framework that allows the progressive development of local value-added processing for high-end food product markets. In this context, there would appear to be a need to ensure transparency in the functioning of supply chains and indeed investment in the autonomous organisation of cocoa producers, linked to wider regional initiatives to progressively develop the cocoa industry from bean to high-end, value-added product.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
